Oscar fits the three things I look for in a Sponsored Deep Dive company:=C2=
=A0
I believe in the company. Table stakes, but true here. I would invest my ow=
n money (although I haven=E2=80=99t yet to avoid that layer of conflict) an=
d I would write about Oscar even if they weren=E2=80=99t paying me (don=E2=
=80=99t tell Oscar!).=C2=A0
The company has lessons applicable beyond the company itself, and potential=
 benefits to you all. There=E2=80=99s a ton to learn here for anyone intere=
sted in taking on regulated, backwards industries with deep-pocketed, scale=
d incumbents. (Hint: it=E2=80=99s a long, hard road, but doable!)
The company=E2=80=99s story is interesting and fits with the trends we=E2=
=80=99re all most interested in. I started writing about healthcare a lot m=
ore at the end of last year, and it=E2=80=99s one of the complex problems I=
 want to dig into more this year. This decade could be to HealthTech what t=
he past one has been to FinTech.=C2=A0
Beyond those three things, Oscar is a special one. It=E2=80=99s the only he=
alth insurance provider I=E2=80=99ve actually chosen for myself (way back i=
n 2013), one of NYC=E2=80=99s most successful startups of the past decade, =
and my favorite kind of company: one whose complexity means that the market=
 has a hard time understanding it.=C2=A0
That complexity comes from the fact that Oscar is trying to be two things a=
t once: an insurance company and a tech platform. It=E2=80=99s a big bet --=
 those are two very different businesses -- but if it pays off, they have t=
he chance to make the healthcare experience meaningfully better.=C2=A0
Plus, while it=E2=80=99s no longer private, it=E2=80=99s still very much an=
 underdog in an industry full of giant incumbents, just like a startup. Des=
pite its success, people still assume the giants will hold their positions =
for decades. Maybe that=E2=80=99s true in insurance in a way that it hasn=
=E2=80=99t been for any other industry, but that=E2=80=99s not the bet I=E2=
=80=99d make.=C2=A0
Let me put the disclaimer/disclosure right up front:=C2=A0
Disclaimer/Disclosure: THIS IS NOT INVESTMENT ADVICE! It never is, but that=
=E2=80=99s particularly true in an industry like insurance in which I=E2=80=
=99ve spent much less time. This is for educational and entertainment purpo=
ses only. Do your own diligence. I decided not to buy any OSCR since I knew=
 I was writing this piece, although I may buy some after sending. This will=
 likely be my stance on public company deep dives going forward. Thrive Cap=
ital, a large shareholder in Oscar, is an LP in Not Boring Capital.=C2=A0
And let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
The Oscar Puzzle
In late 2013, when I left the cushy confines of Bank of America Merrill Lyn=
ch and its gold-plated corporate insurance plan to head to a small Canadian=
 startup that hadn=E2=80=99t even established a US entity, I was given a bu=
dget and told to go find my own health insurance. Oddly, I knew exactly wha=
t health insurance I wanted to get: Oscar [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c=
/eJxFUMtuxCAM_JrlGPFKlhw49NLfQDzcBC2BCJxG-fuym0Mly5Y9Go9mvEVYSr30XhqSdzN47a=
AznC0BIlRyNKgmBs0mrsQoZxK0DEyNisRmfirAZmPSWA8g--FS9BZjyR8GpXwkq_Z8DpRZG6SXl=
I4g3fScxqdnyrqn5POta48QIXvQ8Av1KhlI0ivi3h7i68G_e53nOayxNG_r4MvWLyRqTjmnjAnW=
X3Mx8EHIoIKdlbdKBsdgcHx_pWtkD0m3hQ_tcA2tf71fkKpzQVdqzEuHX6vdIH2AbsX0uR054mU=
gW5cg3C7xDuvj2yyQofYQg7HYI5KcKi4Fm8R0u-ox9FWp96Erh9JZ-V_0D_eMgM8].=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99d seen the ads on the subways: =E2=80=9CHi, we=E2=80=99re Oscar, =
a new kind of health insurance company.=E2=80=9D I loved the clean look. Th=
ey used *tech*. I was now in =E2=80=9Ctech.=E2=80=9D They were from New Yor=
k. I lived in New York. It was a no-brainer.=C2=A0
And when that clean welcome box showed up -- a welcome box! from an insuran=
ce company! -- I knew I=E2=80=99d made the right choice.=C2=A0
(I checked with the company, and I was Member #5,540. At Oscar=E2=80=99s cu=
rrent 594,000 members, that means I was in the first 1% of people ever to s=
ign up.)
Little friendly touches like that box were all part of Oscar=E2=80=99s orig=
inal vision of building a health insurance company that could help its memb=
ers navigate the healthcare system like a doctor in the family would.=C2=A0
Since I signed up, Oscar has grown membership over 100x. It=E2=80=99s on a =
multi-billion dollar revenue run rate. It launched a tech platform, +Oscar,=
 and partnered with leading health systems like Cleveland Clinic. It went p=
ublic=E2=80=A6 and its stock is getting crushed.=C2=A0
Oscar IPO=E2=80=99d on March 3rd at $39 per share and started trading at $3=
6 per share, good for a market cap just north of $7 billion. Since then, it=
=E2=80=99s down nearly 77%, its market cap hovering around $1.5 billion.=C2=
=A0
It=E2=80=99s underperforming both the major indices=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
=E2=80=A6and the traditional health insurance companies, like UnitedHealth,=
 Cigna, Anthem, and even Humana, whose stock has struggled more than its pe=
ers as of late.
On the surface, the mystery is solved simply: Oscar isn=E2=80=99t profitabl=
e yet.=C2=A0
Say what you want about the traditional US health insurance industry (OK, f=
ine, twist my arm: it=E2=80=99s confusing, inefficient, expensive, antiquat=
ed, and about 20 years behind on UX), but those companies print money. In Q=
3 2021, UnitedHealth, the most profitable, made $4.1 billion on $72.3 billi=
on in revenue.=C2=A0
Oscar, on the other hand, loses money on every patient on average. In healt=
h insurance terms, its combined ratio [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJx=
FkM2OhSAMhZ_msjTyp7hgMZt5DQO0eslVMIDX-PaDupgEaGjTntPPmYJzTKfeYi7kesZybqgDHn=
nBUjCRPWMaPWjaMcWlGAhoAVRJRXwep4S4Gr_oknYk224X70zxMdwdbcskeeveTQOCsHxSE-u7D=
mFQEnrZSsOlnPpH1-zgMTjU-MV0xoBk0e9StvziPy_2W89xHI0PX8wlbgjeNC6uNV1NrrlGd924=
Wh8Q0mWiMXkjXrOWsZZSTkX1wxvWcAEKzKCcUQIsxcay7bOckr5Eu86sybvNxbjPNZ8kHWKxMfk=
w1_LnbVZc7kJddqxx3YMv54jB2AXh4VAenDeZccaA1Q7CaEqFKFirmOC0492zdwVVv0pdiaoMsX=
aFf9E_fqGN5g] is greater than 100%. In Q3 2021, Oscar put up an adjusted EB=
ITDA loss of $189 million on $673 million in revenue. Oscar=E2=80=99s stock=
 had started to recover into Q3 earnings, but fell when the company reporte=
d that its medical loss ratio (MLR) =E2=80=93 the percentage of premium it =
pays out for care =E2=80=93 shot up from 82.4% in Q2 to 99.7% in Q3 thanks =
to an unfavorable risk adjustment data validation (essentially an insurance=
 payment audit and true-up, read more here if you really want [https://emai=
l.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUcGOpCAQ_ZrmphHEHjxwmGQzt8lMupO9GoTSZlvBQNnGv98azW=
YTAqkqXr1Xr6xBGGPa9RIzsp-rw30BHWDLEyBCYmuG1Hmn-VWoupEtc1o6rhrFfO6GBDAbP2lMK=
7Bl7SdvDfoYDkRViYY9tLRvrWqGemjbng9KiBaugxoG-da7qoHh5DWr8xAsaHhB2mMANukH4pIv=
9ftFfNDZtq20cy7H-KLoBhlMso_ijsSY0dtc_DJoChNccd8zwpzp22cMHmPyYSy-UxyTObPgSGi=
C4ubzs3h3f9aMMwQ8O_w2k3fHGP8wBPkiWS8PG_NaVEJUnNdc0oR1KcpaOuVMq6xR0vUcyl4sz2=
lv-EVW8yjKvPYZjX2WNs4s6RCxPyRR-fkwM0xHgezr6J1XUrx3EEw_gTudxXNBh9fdCAESLc51B=
mktUlRKyJpf6-vpJFlPoVI_CWJ2kVDhP-lfTRSsVA]) and, of course, COVID.=C2=A0
Oscar=E2=80=99s membership grew 41% YoY, from 420k to 594k, and revenue gre=
w 63%, but the simple bear case would be that, amending the old joke for he=
alth insurance, you can=E2=80=99t lose money on every managed life and make=
 it up in volume.=C2=A0
But still, Oscar is trading below 1x its current revenue run rate, growing =
very fast, and signing up big partners to its software platform, +Oscar. It=
 feels like an overreaction.=C2=A0
Besides, Oscar wasn=E2=80=99t designed to be profitable yet. In fact, it=E2=
=80=99s doing two unprofitable things at the same time: building an insuran=
ce company and a tech platform from scratch. Both require real scale to bec=
ome profitable, and Oscar=E2=80=99s bet is that by combining both, they=E2=
=80=99ll be able to achieve more scale, deliver better care, and generate b=
etter margins over the long-term than either side could alone.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s why Oscar is making three decades-long, interconnected bets:
Bet #1: Technology can meaningfully improve member engagement, which leads =
to a better insurance business.
Oscar believes that by building a better experience, it can increase member=
 engagement, by increasing member engagement, it can better guide its membe=
rs=E2=80=99 care, and that by guiding its members care, it can create bette=
r long-term health outcomes at a lower cost.=C2=A0
The pithy way to explain this piece of the strategy is that an ounce of pre=
vention is better than a pound of cure.=C2=A0
Bet #2: A better, tech-powered insurance business will help Oscar sell its =
technology to hospital systems who want to take risk, improving margins and=
 increasing revenue without increasing Oscar=E2=80=99s risk.
In 2018, Oscar launched what would become +Oscar, its tech platform that le=
ts health systems and other insurers tap into all of the tech that Oscar ha=
s built over the past decade.=C2=A0
To understand this piece of the strategy, think Amazon and AWS. Oscar has s=
pent a decade building and battle-testing its own proprietary tech, and now=
 it=E2=80=99s selling that tech to others who need it and earning software =
margins in the process. Plus, those customers give Oscar scale.=C2=A0
Bet #3: Turning its tech into a platform for third-parties will build scale=
 into both the insurance and tech businesses, which will help improve care =
and lower costs.=C2=A0
Combining Oscar=E2=80=99s insurance business with its +Oscar partners=E2=80=
=99 =E2=80=93 like the Cleveland Clinic and Montefiore =E2=80=93 will give =
Oscar the scale it needs to build a huge, profitable insurance business. Sc=
ale is useful in two ways here:=C2=A0
Insurance Business. More scale means more leverage over the participants in=
 its supply chain, better terms with reinsurers (reinsurance makes up a hug=
e chunk of insurers=E2=80=99 costs), more ability to convince providers to =
join the network, and a lower admin ratio (amortize administrative costs ov=
er more members).=C2=A0=C2=A0
Tech Platform. By opening its tech up as a set of primitives for others in =
the ecosystem to build with, it will get more data on which types of interv=
entions, digital and physical, work best for which types of patients, and a=
ny campaigns it builds for one partner can be copy-pasted and used by any p=
artner, building network effects into the system. More knowledge should lea=
d to better long-term outcomes, and lower costs.
The best way to think about this piece of the business is like Shopify: arm=
ing the rebels (in this case, health systems and care providers) in order t=
o compete with the giant incumbent health insurers.
Taken together, it=E2=80=99s a long-term series of bets which is, understan=
dably, confusing to investors in the short-term. As The Abstract Investor s=
ummarized [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkU2OhCAQhU_T7DTyo9ILFrOZa5g=
SSiUiGChn4u2H7l5MQqBeVSrv5cMC4Zrybc5UiL2uie4TTcTfEpAIM7sK5sk7wwehZa-ezBnluO=
4182VaMuIBPhjKF7LzmoO3QD7F90bXiZ5tpu-HxXZSS8nHZdD8uWC_zOOo3cDtKPTHFy7nMVo0-=
IP5ThFZMBvRWR7y6yG-6ymIu48rhHOD1qajtiCTtwFrpZTSXIkmFQu52RACbU2hZPfm8OWKDnNV=
yTUQXfOWPxAudMwb0QnRcS65qoFlK1qpnHbw1Ba0cjPHdhbnHu6eP1R3rKIt11wI7P4KwbKJiea=
Ua7I63jc4MLwHlcZU3-OKnu4JI8wB3QcUfXi_0U0rRsz1H9wEVCkr0WmhJB_k8AFTSVap9atRnV=
2qW_Hf9A8qkpkS], the challenge, and opportunity, is that:
Many tech analysts aren't paying attention to insurance, while insurance an=
alysts won't quite know how to look at a highly tech-stacked insurance comp=
any. That presents a potential opportunity for those that can figure out th=
e murky puzzle.
That theory checks out, particularly when you look at how Oscar has perform=
ed compared to other public health insurtech companies: Bright Health Group=
 and Clover.
Oscar has traded in-line with those companies despite the fact that the bus=
inesses are very different. If you need scale and tech to disrupt health in=
surance, neither Bright nor Clover has both. Bright is essentially a rollup=
 and partnerships play with little meaningful tech; Clover is a tech player=
 in the Medicare Advantage space with only a quarter of the =E2=80=9Clives =
under management=E2=80=9D that Oscar has, and no platform play like +Oscar =
to achieve scale.=C2=A0
Oscar is the only player in the space that has a shot at achieving scale th=
rough technology.
The fact that these three very different companies are trading in line, and=
 falling while the incumbents=E2=80=99 stock prices rise, is weird. It mean=
s the market is saying that, unlike practically every other industry in the=
 world, health insurance will be impervious to disruption from technology-f=
irst companies. That seems off. I think the Oscar baby is being thrown out =
with the insurtech bath water.
So today, we=E2=80=99re going to dive in and try to piece together the murk=
y puzzle. I=E2=80=99m not a healthcare analyst, and I don=E2=80=99t even tr=
y to play one on the internet, but I do love a good puzzle. We=E2=80=99ll c=
over:=C2=A0
How Health Insurance Works
Oscar=E2=80=99s Origins: The Hipster Health Insurance=C2=A0
Oscar: A Tech-Enabled Insurance Business=C2=A0
+Oscar: An Insurance-Enabled Tech Platform=C2=A0
Putting Together the Puzzle =C2=A0
To understand the bets that Oscar=E2=80=99s making, we need to understand h=
ow health insurance businesses work and where they=E2=80=99re broken. I pro=
mise I=E2=80=99ll make it as not boring as possible.
How Health Insurance Works
Almost every industry is easier to understand than it appears at first glan=
ce. It=E2=80=99s just about understanding the vocabulary, how businesses ma=
ke money, and what levers they have to pull. Health insurance, while there=
=E2=80=99s a ton of complexity in the details, is not hard to understand at=
 a high level.=C2=A0
To understand how US health insurance works at the highest level (convenien=
tly, that=E2=80=99s also the only level at which I understand it), let=E2=
=80=99s look at three things:=C2=A0
The Size and Composition of the Market
The Health Insurance Profit Formula=C2=A0
The Two Main Reimbursement models
The Size and Composition of the Market
Healthcare in the US is an unimaginably large market.=C2=A0
Americans spend $4 trillion on healthcare per year -- 18% of GDP -- and 75%=
 of that passes through insurance companies. Half of Americans have group, =
or employer-sponsored, health insurance, 35% have government insurance (Med=
icaid, Medicare, or Military), 9% are uninsured, and 5.9% have non-group pl=
ans. This last group, the individual market, is where Oscar started.=C2=A0
The employer market is the monster here. It=E2=80=99s probably what you=E2=
=80=99re familiar with. Insurance companies sell plans to your company, and=
 you get to choose from among their plans. In this system, your insurance i=
s tied to your job, and people bounce from insurer to insurer as they move =
jobs. That means that no one insurer is incentivized to optimize for long-t=
erm health, so they optimize for the short-term, which often drives up long=
-term costs.=C2=A0
To learn more about the health insurance industry, Oscar=E2=80=99s backstor=
y, its tech-enabled insurance business, its insurance-enabled tech business=
, and how the puzzle fits together=E2=80=A6
