1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Oscar&#8217;s=
 <strong>membership grew 41%</strong> YoY, from 420k to 594k, and <strong>r=
evenue grew 63%</strong>, but the simple bear case would be that, amending =
the old joke for health insurance, you <strong>can&#8217;t lose money on ev=
ery managed life and make it up in volume</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">But s=
till, Oscar is trading below 1x its current revenue run rate, growing very =
fast, and signing up big partners to its software platform, +Oscar. It feel=
s like an overreaction.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Besides, Oscar wasn&#8217;t desig=
ned to be profitable yet. In fact, it&#8217;s doing <strong>two unprofitabl=
e things at the same time</strong>: building an insurance company and a tec=
h platform from scratch. Both require real <strong>scale </strong>to become=
 profitable, and Oscar&#8217;s bet is that by combining both, they&#8217;ll=
 be able to achieve more scale, deliver better care, and generate better ma=
rgins over the long-term than either side could alone.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Th=
at&#8217;s why Oscar is making three decades-long, interconnected bets:</p>=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 1em 0;"><strong>Bet #1:</strong> <strong>Technology can meaningfully impro=
ve member engagement, which leads to a better insurance business.</strong><=
/p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 1em 0;">Oscar believes that by building a better experience, it can inc=
rease member engagement, by increasing member engagement, it can better gui=
de its members&#8217; care, and that by guiding its members care, it can cr=
eate better long-term health outcomes at a lower cost.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Th=
e pithy way to explain this piece of the strategy is that an <strong>ounce =
of prevention is better than a pound of cure</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><s=
trong>Bet #2:</strong> <strong>A better, tech-powered insurance business wi=
ll help Oscar sell its technology to hospital systems who want to take risk=
, improving margins and increasing revenue without increasing Oscar&#8217;s=
 risk.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In 2018, Oscar launched what would become <stro=
ng>+Oscar</strong>, its tech platform that lets health systems and other in=
surers tap into all of the tech that Oscar has built over the past decade.&=
nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 1em 0;">To understand this piece of the strategy, think <strong>A=
mazon and AWS</strong>. Oscar has spent a decade building and battle-testin=
g its own proprietary tech, and now it&#8217;s selling that tech to others =
who need it and earning software margins in the process. Plus, those custom=
ers give Oscar scale.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>Bet #3:</strong> <strong>Tu=
rning its tech into a platform for third-parties will build scale into both=
 the insurance and tech businesses, which will help improve care and lower =
costs.&nbsp;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Combining Oscar&#8217;s insurance busines=
s with its +Oscar partners&#8217; &#8211; like the Cleveland Clinic and Mon=
